04629nam a22007095i 9780824837594DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20102010hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248375947 a10.1515/97808248375942doi  a(DE-B1597)484678  a(OCoLC)663885752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a895.1/3520822200aHeroes of China's Great Leap Forward :bTwo Stories /ced. by Richard King. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tA Brief Biography of Li Shuangshuang -- tThe Story of the Criminal Li Tongzhong -- tGlossary -- tAbout the Editor0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHeroes of China’s Great Leap Forward presents contrasting narratives of the most ambitious and disastrous mass movement in modern Chinese history. The objective of the Great Leap, when it was launched in the late 1950s, was to catapult China into the ranks of the great military and industrial powers with no assistance from the outside world; it resulted in a famine that killed tens of millions of the nation’s peasants.Li Zhun’s "A Brief Biography of Li Shuangshuang," written while the movement was underway, celebrates the Great Leap as it was supposed to be: a time of optimism, dynamism, and shared purpose. A spirited young peasant woman, freed from the restrictions of home life, launches a canteen and wins the recognition of authorities and the admiration of her husband. The story—and the film that followed it—made Li Shuangshuang the greatest fictional heroine of the Great Leap. In contrast, Zhang Yigong’s short novel The Story of the Criminal Li Tongzhong, written two decades later, was one of the first works published in China to suggest a much darker side to the Great Leap. A village official leads a raid on a state granary to feed starving peasants; he is later arrested and dies a criminal. Although Zhang stopped short of portraying the horrors of famine, his tone of moral outrage provides a rejoinder to the triumphalism of "Li Shuangshuang."The stories are accompanied by an introduction to the Great Leap and portraits of the two writers, including their recollections of that traumatic time and the creation of their very different heroes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aChinese fictiony20th centuryvTranslations into English. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aKing, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYigong, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhun, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483759440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837594.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK